We are using dbUnit to setup and tear down our db data in tests. We are using specific db. And in order to provide proper DATATYPE_FACTORY we have to use the following code:
~~~
@BeforeTest
init() {
        DataSourceDatabaseTester databaseTester = new DataSourceDatabaseTester(dataSource);
...
        databaseTester.setOperationListener(new DefaultOperationListener() {
            @Override
            public void connectionRetrieved(IDatabaseConnection connection) {
                connection.getConfig().setProperty(DatabaseConfig.PROPERTY_DATATYPE_FACTORY, new HsqldbDataTypeFactory());
                super.connectionRetrieved(connection);
            }
        });
            databaseTester.onSetup();
}
~~~

This code to configure data type factory (hsqldb) is not very handsome. Can you for example allow providing DatabaseConfig into DataSourceDatabaseTester. Or can you detect database type automatically.

Original message posted in the mailling list. ML

\---

FROM: bill pope
DATE: 03/21/2002 11:27:09
SUBJECT:  \[dbunit-user\] FlatXmlDataSet and null values 

Hi,
I am having a problem when loading data using the 
FlatXmlDataSet format.
This is just an export and a load. The code works fine 
if I use XmlDataSet
rather than FlatXmlDataSet. Upon examination I 
wondered if the problem was
that this particular table has null values in a couple 
of columns and it is
one of these columns that seems to trigger the error.

Regards

Bill


public void testDbLoadAll\(\) throws Exception
\{
DatabaseOperation.DELETE\_ALL.execute\(myconn, 
getCombinedDataSet\(\)\);

DatabaseOperation.CLEAN\_INSERT.execute\(myconn,
getCombinedDataSet\(\)\);
\}

protected IDataSet getCombinedDataSet\(\) throws 
Exception
\{
// THIS GIVES THE ERROR SHOWN
IDataSet staticUserDataSet = new FlatXmlDataSet
\(new
FileInputStream\(&amp;quot;staticdataflat.xml&amp;quot;\)\);
IDataSet dynamicUserDataSet = new 
FlatXmlDataSet\(new
FileInputStream\(&amp;quot;dynamicdataflat.xml&amp;quot;\)\);

// THIS WORKS FINE
IDataSet staticUserDataSet = new XmlDataSet\(new
FileInputStream\(&amp;quot;staticdata.xml&amp;quot;\)\);
IDataSet dynamicUserDataSet = new XmlDataSet
\(new
FileInputStream\(&amp;quot;dynamicdata.xml&amp;quot;\)\);

return new CompositeDataSet\(staticUserDataSet, 
dynamicUserDataSet\);
\}

Error condition when running with a FlatXmlDataSet

org.dbunit.dataset.NoSuchColumnException: &amp;lt;LOGONTIME&amp;gt; 
not a column of table
&amp;lt;CORE.VOICESERVERDEFINITIONS&amp;gt; 	at
org.dbunit.dataset.AbstractTable.assertValidColumn
\(AbstractTable.java:51\)
at org.dbunit.dataset.xml.FlatXmlTable.getValue
\(FlatXmlTable.java:94\) 	at
org.dbunit.operation.AbstractBatchOperation.execute
\(AbstractBatchOperation.j
ava:93\) 	at
org.dbunit.operation.CompositeOperation.execute
\(CompositeOperation.java:68\)
at
org.dbunit.TestDatabaseProcess2.testDbLoadAll
\(TestDatabaseProcess2.java:140\)

The row in question is shown below in both formats

FlatXmlDataSet
&amp;lt;CORE.VOICESERVERDEFINITIONS VSID='1' LINES='64' 
NAME='VS1'
LOCATION='LOC1' STATUS='4' ACTIVE='0'/&amp;gt;

XmlDataSet
&amp;lt;table name='CORE.VOICESERVERDEFINITIONS'&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;column&amp;gt;VSID&amp;lt;/column&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;column&amp;gt;LINES&amp;lt;/column&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;column&amp;gt;NAME&amp;lt;/column&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;column&amp;gt;LOCATION&amp;lt;/column&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;column&amp;gt;LOGONTIME&amp;lt;/column&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;column&amp;gt;LOGOFFTIME&amp;lt;/column&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;column&amp;gt;STATUS&amp;lt;/column&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;column&amp;gt;ACTIVE&amp;lt;/column&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;row&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;value&amp;gt;1&amp;lt;/value&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;value&amp;gt;64&amp;lt;/value&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;value&amp;gt;VS1&amp;lt;/value&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;value&amp;gt;LOC1&amp;lt;/value&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;null/&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;null/&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;value&amp;gt;4&amp;lt;/value&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;value&amp;gt;0&amp;lt;/value&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;/row&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;/table&amp;gt;

DbUnit is not using the SQL Escape Syntax for DATE,
TIME and TIMESTAMP. This may cause problem with some 
DBMS. 

Workaround:

Use the following code in the 
DataSetUtils.getSqlValueString\(\) method.

public static String getSqlValueString\(Object 
value, DataType dataType\)
throws TypeCastException
\{
if \(value == null\)
\{
return &amp;quot;NULL&amp;quot;;
\}

String stringValue = asString\(value\);
if \(dataType == DataType.DATE\)
\{
return &amp;quot;\{d '&amp;quot; + stringValue + &amp;quot;'\}&amp;quot;;
\}

if \(dataType == DataType.TIME\)
\{
return &amp;quot;\{t '&amp;quot; + stringValue + &amp;quot;'\}&amp;quot;;
\}

if \(dataType == DataType.TIMESTAMP\)
\{
return &amp;quot;\{ts '&amp;quot; + stringValue + &amp;quot;'\}&amp;quot;;
\}

if \(\!dataType.isNumber\(\)\)
\{
stringValue = &amp;quot;'&amp;quot; + stringValue + &amp;quot;'&amp;quot;;
\}

return stringValue;
\}

I have a table that has a column referencing the parent 
row:

&amp;lt;MyTable id='a'&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;MyTable id='b' parent\_id='a'&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;MyTable id='c1' parent\_id='b'&amp;gt;
&amp;lt;MyTable id='c2' parent\_id='b'&amp;gt;

It is inserted/refreshed into the database properly, but it 
can't be deleted because the delete operation operates 
on the rows in the given order.  Attempting to delete the 
first row causes an error because it violates a foreign 
key constraint on the parent\_id column of the next row.

Would it be possible to modify the delete operation to 
delete rows in reverse order?
